  "prompt": "Which are the best british fictional books?",
  "response": "There are many excellent British fictional books, but some of the most highly regarded and influential include:\n\n1. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen (1813)** - A classic novel of manners that explores themes of love, reputation, and class in early 19th-century England.\n   \n2. **\"1984\" by George Orwell (1949)** - A dystopian novel that provides a powerful commentary on totalitarianism, surveillance, and individualism.\n\n3. **\"Jane Eyre\" by Charlotte Bront\u00eb (1847)** - A bildungsroman that follows the experiences of the titular character, an orphaned girl who becomes a governess and falls in love with her employer.\n\n4. **\"Wuthering Heights\" by Emily Bront\u00eb (1847)** - A dark, passionate tale of love and revenge set on the Yorkshire moors.\n\n5. **\"Great Expectations\" by Charles Dickens (1861)** - A coming-of-age story about an orphan named Pip and his growth and personal development.\n\n6. **\"Frankenstein\" by Mary Shelley (1818)** - A novel that blends Gothic and Romantic elements, exploring themes of creation, ambition, and humanity.\n\n7. **\"The Picture of Dorian Gray\" by Oscar Wilde (1890)** - A novel about the consequences of vanity and moral corruption, centered around a man whose portrait ages while he remains young.\n\n8. **\"To the Lighthouse\" by Virginia Woolf (1927)** - A modernist novel that examines themes of time, memory, and personal relationships through a family\u2019s visits to a lighthouse.\n\n9. **\"Middlemarch\" by George Eliot (1871-1872)** - A multi-faceted work that examines the lives, social ambitions, and struggles of various characters within a provincial English town.\n\n10. **\"Harry Potter series\" by J.K. Rowling (1997-2007)** - A globally popular fantasy series about the magical adventures and struggles of a young wizard named Harry Potter.\n\nThese novels are celebrated for their timeless themes, complex characters, and the richness of their language and storytelling.",
